In music, '''sotto voce''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|s|ɒ|t|oʊ|_|ˈ|v|oʊ|tʃ|i|,_|-|tʃ|eɪ}},<ref>[https://www.ahdictionary.com/word/search.html?q=sotto%20voce American Heritage Dictionary]</ref><ref>[http://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/sotto-voce Collins English Dictionary]</ref> {{IPA-it|ˈsotto ˈvoːtʃe|lang}}; {{langnf||Italian|"under the voice"}}) is a dramatic lowering of the vocal or instrumental volume — not necessarily [[Dynamics (music)|''pianissimo'']], but a definitely hushed tonal quality. 
Examples of sotto voce include:
* In the [[Lacrimosa (Requiem)|Lacrimosa]] from [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart]]'s [[Requiem (Mozart)|Requiem]], in which the singers lower their volume for emphasis.{{citation needed|date=June 2017|reason=Claim about a person's use of a specific dynamic in a public domain score.}} 
* At the beginning of the third movement of [[Ludwig van Beethoven|Beethoven]]'s [[String Quartet No. 15 (Beethoven)|String Quartet No. 15, Op. 132]], in which the strings play with a hushed quality before later playing with renewed strength.{{citation needed|date=June 2017|reason=Claim about a person's use of a specific dynamic in a public domain score.}} 
* The second part of [[Chopin]]'s [[Nocturne in C minor, Op 48 No 1]], which is marked ''sotto voce e sostenuto''; this is used to 'hold back the drama and keep us in suspense'.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nocturne in C minor, Op 48 No 1 - Hyperion Records - CDs, MP3 and Lossless downloads |url=https://www.hyperion-records.co.uk/tw.asp?w=W3375 |website=www.hyperion-records.co.uk |accessdate=28 June 2018 |language=en}}</ref>

